metadata.name: Moon Sun Ocean #122
metadata.description:
The secret to happiness is to simplify as much as possible. The details surrounding us must be said goodbye as soon as possible. The best thing we can do is to get started early and get rid of additional complexities as soon as possible. After that, we'll be able to breathe... After that, life will begin again!
There will be many words in this interpretation, despite its simplicity.
Made by p5.js
press 's' to save original size

metadata.name: Specter of Fears #88
metadata.description:
In the dreamlike landscape of our minds, the specter of fears is like a wraith, ever-present and ethereal. It whispers in our ear, reminding us of all the things we dare not face. It is a shadow that falls across our hearts, casting a pall of doubt and uncertainty. But even as it haunts us, we must remember that it is a part of us. We must learn to accept its presence, and to use it to our advantage. For fear is not always a curse, it is a guide that shows us where we must grow stronger. It is a companion that walks with us through the dark night, illuminating the path ahead. By embracing our fears, we find the courage to face them, and to overcome them. We find the strength to live fully, to love fiercely, and to pursue our dreams with abandon.

Controls :

metadata.name: Bayeux #89
metadata.description:
Each output is generated by layering Blender renders.

'Bayeux' explores the bold simplicity and beauty of Bauhaus design ideas, with an arrangment of simple bauhaus-inspired shapes in a colorful, striking design. The addition of smaller shapes arranged in a checkerboard style gives some outputs an heraldic feel.

To download a 1500x2000px PNG:
Click/tap 'open', then click/tap the image to make a "Download image" button appear.

metadata.name: Eucalyptus and Sagebrush #81
metadata.description:
Eucalyptus and Sagebrush is inspired by the eucalyptus trees and sagebrush found in California. These plants, and the hills they inhabit, have long been a source of beauty and adventure in my life, and I find myself repeatedly drawn back to them. The sunsets in coastal California are a perfect compliment to these hills, and I set out to represent that combination in this work.

Each iteration of this algorithm feels, to me, like a glimpse out of a car window on a drive up the coast, a pause on a cool morning hike, or a memory of tearing through sharp underbrush with good company.

Stylistically and texturally, I drew from landscapes rendered in oil pastels, placing thousands of tiny circles, alluding to the effect of depositing particles of color onto paper. 

I hope that this work evokes in the viewer the feelings of peace, wildness, and adventure that I feel when I watch the sun set over these hills.

Nat Sarkissian


Notes:
- Append ‚Äú&mag=N‚Äù to the end of the URL in live mode to specify a resolution multiplier. It will render the image N times larger than the size of your window. If you have specified anything greater than 1, a download will start automatically once the rendering is done. The maximum resolution seems to be limited by what your web browser allows. I have been able to output up to 11140px tall and wide using Firefox, which should be enough detail for prints up to 37x37 inches. I recommend keeping the console open while attempting larger renders. It will show you if you have attempted too large a render for your system. N can be any positive whole or decimal number greater than or equal to 1.

metadata.name: Lineamenta #15
metadata.description:
Outlines can be seen as a reflection of the human desire for order and structure in the world around us. Just as we use outlines to organize our thoughts and ideas, we also seek to impose order on the natural world through our scientific understanding and categorization of phenomena.

However, the act of outlining also highlights the limitations of our understanding and the subjectivity of our perspectives. An outline can never fully capture the complexity and nuance of a subject, and different individuals may have vastly different perspectives on the same topic.

In this way, outlines can be seen as both a tool for understanding and a reminder of the inherent uncertainty and subjectivity of our perceptions. It is a reminder that our understanding of the world is always evolving and that there's always more to discover.

- Press [d] to download your copy of Lineamenta.

~ Made in p5.js and chroma.js ~ by simplisto ~ December 2022

metadata.name: Sabler #252
metadata.description:
'Sabler', an anagram of 'Albers', is a generative homage to the work of the Bauhaus textile artist Anni Albers.

The aesthetic of this piece and its proportions are guided by the Golden Ratio (1.618 : 1) and as such, each part of the composition relates in some way to its larger self. 

As lines playfully extend and overlap one another from various grid segments, patterns appear, 'ghost' shadings emerge and complexity is implied even with the use of very simple elements. In line with that simplicity, colors and palettes have also been kept to a minimum.

There are no rarities or special features, other than for you to enjoy the unique qualities of your piece!

You can save a high resolution 3000px x 3000px PNG of your edition by pressing the 'S' key.

metadata.name: Ordinary Places #200
metadata.description:
‚ÄúOrdinary Places‚Äù is a fully-coded meditation on the poetic beauty of everyday landscapes. 

The architectural characters in these landscapes include water towers (inspired by Bernd & Hilla Becher‚Äôs ‚ÄúWater Tower‚Äù photography series), gas stations (inspired by Ed Ruscha‚Äôs ‚Äú26 Gasoline Stations‚Äù photography book), and barns (inspired by childhood memories on my grandfather‚Äôs farm). 

Yet, while these scenes may seem ordinary upon first glance, something darker lurks beneath the surface. The hidden secrets of these Ordinary Places can only be revealed through the minting process. In this sense, the outputs are not merely a collection individual scenes, but instead, a coherent world animated by shared themes and narratives.     

Pressing the down arrow saves the coded output as a .png image.
